      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὡς δοῦλοι θεοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 2:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): “Intelliguntur servi secundum carnem, diversi a liberis. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", sed iidem servi Dei,” Bengel. According to Maimonides, no slave could be a prophet, but as in Christ there was neither Jew nor Gentile, neither male nor female, so in Him there was neither bond nor free (see also Keil, ",
